IOT_QUESTIONS_PART1 = [{'question': 'What are the five main components of an IoT architecture and which represents the largest attack surface?', 'options': [{'text': 'Devices, connectivity, edge gateways, cloud platform and mobile apps — with the cloud platform representing the largest attack surface', 'explanation': 'While the cloud platform is a significant attack surface IoT devices themselves represent the largest attack surface due to their sheer number, weak security configurations, default credentials and inability to be easily patched once deployed at scale.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Devices, connectivity, edge gateways, cloud platform and mobile apps — with IoT devices representing the largest attack surface due to their volume weak security and deployment at scale', 'explanation': 'Correct. IoT devices represent the largest attack surface because they are deployed in enormous numbers, typically have weak default credentials, run unpatched firmware, lack encryption, and are physically accessible. The Mirai botnet demonstrated how compromising millions of IoT devices creates catastrophic attack capability.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'Routers, switches, servers, applications and users — with users representing the largest attack surface', 'explanation': 'This describes a traditional IT architecture not IoT architecture. IoT architecture specifically includes connected devices, edge computing, and cloud platforms designed for machine-to-machine communication.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Sensors, actuators, controllers, networks and applications — with networks representing the largest attack surface', 'explanation': 'While these are OT/ICS components the IoT architecture attack surface is dominated by the devices themselves due to their volume, weak security defaults, and difficulty of patching at scale.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'IoT attack surface by component: devices (billions deployed with weak security), connectivity (unencrypted protocols), edge gateways (pivot points between IoT and corporate networks), cloud platforms (API vulnerabilities and data exposure), and mobile apps (insecure data storage). Devices dominate due to sheer volume and weak security defaults.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Architecture'}, {'question': 'What made the Mirai botnet attack in 2016 a watershed moment for IoT security?', 'options': [{'text': 'It was the first malware to target IoT devices using zero-day vulnerabilities in device firmware', 'explanation': 'Mirai did not use zero-day vulnerabilities. It exploited default credentials — a known and easily preventable vulnerability. This made it even more significant as it demonstrated catastrophic impact from basic security failures.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'It compromised 600000 IoT devices using default credentials and generated the largest DDoS attack ever recorded demonstrating the catastrophic scale of IoT security failures', 'explanation': 'Correct. Mirai scanned the internet for IoT devices with default credentials, compromised approximately 600,000 devices, and generated 1.2Tbps DDoS attacks taking down major internet services. It proved that weak IoT security at scale creates threats capable of disrupting critical internet infrastructure.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'It was the first ransomware attack targeting IoT devices encrypting device firmware for financial extortion', 'explanation': 'Mirai was not ransomware. It was a botnet that used compromised IoT devices for DDoS attacks. The motive was disruption not financial extortion through encryption.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'It demonstrated that IoT devices could be used to steal sensitive personal data from home networks', 'explanation': 'Mirai used compromised IoT devices for DDoS not data theft. The attack targeted internet infrastructure not personal data on home networks.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': "Mirai's legacy: it demonstrated that billions of poorly secured IoT devices create unprecedented DDoS capability, drove regulatory action on IoT security including the UK PSTI Act 2024 banning default passwords, and established that IoT security is a critical infrastructure concern not just a consumer privacy issue.", 'domain': 'IoT Security - Architecture'}, {'question': 'Why is firmware security considered one of the most critical aspects of IoT device security?', 'options': [{'text': 'Firmware security is only important for industrial IoT devices and not relevant to consumer IoT products', 'explanation': 'Firmware security is critical for all IoT devices including consumer products. Consumer IoT devices with vulnerable firmware have been used in major botnet attacks affecting internet infrastructure.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Firmware is the permanent software controlling device hardware and vulnerabilities in it cannot be fixed without updates making insecure firmware a persistent long-term risk', 'explanation': 'Correct. Firmware controls all device hardware functions. Unlike application software firmware vulnerabilities cannot be patched by users without manufacturer updates. Many IoT devices never receive firmware updates leaving known vulnerabilities permanently exploitable for the device lifetime which may be 10 or more years.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'Firmware security only matters during device manufacturing and has no relevance after a device is deployed', 'explanation': 'Firmware security is critically important throughout the device lifecycle. Post-deployment firmware vulnerabilities are exploited regularly and the lack of update mechanisms leaves devices permanently vulnerable.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Firmware vulnerabilities can always be mitigated through network security controls making firmware security a low priority', 'explanation': 'Network controls are compensating controls but do not address all firmware vulnerabilities especially those requiring physical access or affecting device functionality. Firmware security is a primary control not secondary.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'IoT firmware security requirements: secure boot verifying firmware integrity before execution, encrypted firmware storage preventing extraction and analysis, signed firmware updates preventing malicious update installation, and over-the-air update capability ensuring security patches can be deployed. Many legacy IoT devices lack all of these controls.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Architecture'}, {'question': 'What is the OWASP IoT Top 10 and why is it an important reference for IoT security practitioners?', 'options': [{'text': 'The OWASP IoT Top 10 is a list of the ten most popular IoT devices sold globally each year', 'explanation': 'The OWASP IoT Top 10 is a security framework not a product popularity list. It identifies the ten most critical security risks in IoT systems to help practitioners prioritise security efforts.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'The OWASP IoT Top 10 identifies the ten most critical security risks in IoT systems providing a framework for prioritising security controls across the IoT attack surface', 'explanation': 'Correct. The OWASP IoT Top 10 identifies critical risks including weak passwords, insecure network services, insecure ecosystem interfaces, lack of secure update mechanisms, use of insecure components, insufficient privacy protection, insecure data transfer, lack of device management, insecure default settings and lack of physical hardening.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'The OWASP IoT Top 10 is a mandatory compliance framework that all IoT manufacturers must certify against before selling devices', 'explanation': 'The OWASP IoT Top 10 is a guidance framework not a mandatory certification requirement. Compliance is voluntary though it is referenced in security assessments and procurement requirements.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'The OWASP IoT Top 10 only applies to industrial IoT devices and is not relevant to consumer smart home products', 'explanation': 'The OWASP IoT Top 10 applies to all IoT systems including consumer smart home devices, industrial IoT, medical IoT, and smart city infrastructure. It is designed to be broadly applicable across all IoT domains.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'OWASP IoT Top 10 categories: I1 Weak Passwords, I2 Insecure Network Services, I3 Insecure Ecosystem Interfaces, I4 Lack of Secure Update Mechanism, I5 Use of Insecure or Outdated Components, I6 Insufficient Privacy Protection, I7 Insecure Data Transfer and Storage, I8 Lack of Device Management, I9 Insecure Default Settings, I10 Lack of Physical Hardening.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Architecture'}, {'question': 'An IoT security assessment finds that all devices of the same model share identical default credentials that are publicly documented in the vendor manual. What OWASP IoT Top 10 category does this represent and what is the risk?', 'options': [{'text': 'I4 Lack of Secure Update Mechanism — attackers can push malicious firmware updates using the default credentials', 'explanation': 'While default credentials could enable malicious updates the primary OWASP category for default credentials is I1 Weak Passwords. The most direct risk is unauthorised access to device management interfaces.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'I1 Weak Passwords — publicly documented default credentials allow any attacker with internet access to compromise all devices of this model simultaneously', 'explanation': 'Correct. OWASP I1 Weak Passwords covers default credentials that are publicly known. Publicly documented default credentials mean any attacker can access all devices of that model without any hacking skill. This is how Mirai compromised 600,000 devices — by trying default credentials from publicly available vendor manuals.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'I9 Insecure Default Settings — the default configuration is insecure but can be easily remediated by changing settings', 'explanation': 'While default credentials relate to I9 Insecure Default Settings the primary OWASP category for unchanged default passwords is I1 Weak Passwords. The risk is direct unauthorised access not just insecure configuration.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'I6 Insufficient Privacy Protection — the default credentials expose personal data stored on the devices', 'explanation': 'Privacy protection is a secondary concern. The primary risk of public default credentials is complete device compromise giving attackers administrative control not just access to stored data.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'OWASP I1 Weak Passwords is the most exploited IoT vulnerability. Mitigations: require unique credentials per device set at manufacture, implement account lockout after failed attempts, disable default accounts where possible, and monitor for authentication attempts using known default credential lists. The UK PSTI Act 2024 now legally requires unique per-device credentials.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Architecture'}, {'question': 'What is the security significance of an IoT device having an open Telnet service on port 23?', 'options': [{'text': 'Telnet on port 23 is a normal management interface and represents no security concern on IoT devices', 'explanation': 'Telnet transmits all data including credentials in plaintext and has no encryption. It is a critical security vulnerability on any device and should be disabled on production IoT devices.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Telnet transmits all data including credentials in plaintext making it trivially interceptable and providing unauthenticated access if default credentials are unchanged', 'explanation': 'Correct. Telnet has no encryption meaning any attacker on the network can capture credentials in plaintext. Combined with default credentials Telnet provides easy unauthenticated access to IoT devices. Shodan regularly finds millions of IoT devices with open Telnet ports accessible from the internet.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'Telnet on port 23 is only a security concern if the device is connected to the internet but is safe on internal networks', 'explanation': 'Telnet is insecure on any network. Internal network attackers, malware with network access, and compromised devices on the same network can all exploit open Telnet services. Internal network security is not guaranteed.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Telnet is more secure than SSH because it uses a simpler protocol with fewer vulnerabilities', 'explanation': 'Telnet is significantly less secure than SSH. SSH encrypts all communications including credentials. Telnet transmits everything in plaintext. SSH should always replace Telnet for device management.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'Telnet on IoT devices is a critical vulnerability for three reasons: plaintext credential transmission enables credential theft, default credentials combined with Telnet provide immediate device compromise, and internet-exposed Telnet enables remote exploitation at massive scale as demonstrated by Mirai. Replace with SSH or web-based HTTPS management and disable Telnet entirely.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Architecture'}, {'question': 'What is the purpose of a hardware security module (HSM) in IoT device security and what does it protect?', 'options': [{'text': 'An HSM is a physical case that protects IoT devices from physical damage and tampering', 'explanation': 'An HSM is a cryptographic hardware component not a physical protective case. It provides secure key storage and cryptographic operations not physical protection from damage.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'An HSM is a dedicated hardware component that securely stores cryptographic keys and performs cryptographic operations protecting keys from extraction even if the device software is compromised', 'explanation': 'Correct. HSMs store private keys in tamper-resistant hardware meaning even if device software is compromised the cryptographic keys cannot be extracted. This protects device identity certificates, encryption keys, and signing keys from software-based attacks and physical extraction attempts.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'An HSM is a network security appliance that monitors IoT device communications for malicious traffic', 'explanation': 'Network security monitoring is performed by different tools. An HSM is a device-level hardware component providing secure cryptographic key storage and operations on or within the IoT device itself.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'An HSM is only relevant for enterprise IoT deployments and provides no benefit for consumer IoT devices', 'explanation': 'HSMs benefit any IoT deployment where device identity and cryptographic security are important. Many modern consumer IoT platforms including payment terminals and smart meters use HSMs for security.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'HSMs in IoT provide: secure key storage protecting private keys from extraction, hardware-based cryptographic operations for signing and encryption, tamper detection and response destroying keys if physical tampering is detected, and a root of trust for device identity. Examples include TPM chips in enterprise devices and secure elements in payment terminals.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Architecture'}, {'question': 'Why is network segmentation particularly important when deploying IoT devices in an enterprise environment?', 'options': [{'text': 'Network segmentation is only important for IoT devices that store sensitive personal data', 'explanation': 'Network segmentation is important for all IoT devices regardless of data sensitivity. Even IoT devices that store no sensitive data can serve as pivot points into corporate networks if not properly segmented.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'IoT devices typically have weak security controls making them easy pivot points into corporate networks if placed on the same network segment as sensitive systems', 'explanation': 'Correct. IoT devices typically have weaker security than corporate IT systems making them easier to compromise. Without segmentation a compromised IoT device such as a smart TV or IP camera can be used to attack corporate servers, access sensitive data, or serve as a persistent foothold. The Target breach began with a compromised HVAC system on the same network as payment systems.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'Network segmentation for IoT is only needed in manufacturing environments not in offices or retail', 'explanation': 'IoT devices in any environment including offices retail and healthcare represent pivot risks if not segmented. The Target breach involved retail HVAC systems demonstrating that non-manufacturing environments also require IoT segmentation.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Network segmentation prevents IoT devices from functioning correctly and should be avoided', 'explanation': 'Properly implemented network segmentation allows IoT devices to function while restricting their ability to communicate with unnecessary systems. IoT devices typically only need to communicate with specific cloud endpoints and management systems not the entire corporate network.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'IoT network segmentation: place all IoT devices on dedicated VLANs, restrict IoT device communication to required cloud endpoints only, prevent IoT-to-corporate network communication, monitor all traffic leaving the IoT VLAN, and implement DNS filtering on the IoT segment. The 2013 Target breach cost  million and began with an unsegmented HVAC IoT system.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Architecture'}, {'question': 'What is the security risk of an IoT device that updates its firmware automatically without verifying the cryptographic signature of the update?', 'options': [{'text': 'Automatic firmware updates without signature verification only risk installing updates that reduce device performance', 'explanation': 'Performance impact is a minor concern. The critical security risk is that without signature verification any party who can intercept or spoof the update mechanism can install malicious firmware giving them complete control of the device.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Without signature verification an attacker who can intercept or spoof the update source can install malicious firmware giving complete control of all devices receiving that update', 'explanation': 'Correct. Unsigned firmware updates allow malicious firmware installation through: man-in-the-middle attacks intercepting update traffic, DNS spoofing redirecting update requests to attacker servers, or compromise of the update server itself. Signed firmware ensures only manufacturer-approved firmware can be installed.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'Automatic firmware updates without signatures only affect devices when they are connected to public WiFi networks', 'explanation': 'Unsigned firmware attacks can be executed on any network not just public WiFi. DNS spoofing, BGP hijacking, and update server compromise can affect devices on any network type.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'Signature verification is only necessary for firmware updates delivered over the internet not for local network updates', 'explanation': 'Signature verification is important regardless of update delivery method. Local network attackers, compromised internal update servers, and supply chain attacks can all deliver malicious firmware without internet delivery.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'Secure IoT firmware update requirements: cryptographic signature verification using manufacturer private key, encrypted update delivery preventing interception, integrity checking confirming update was not corrupted in transit, rollback capability allowing recovery from failed updates, and authenticated update triggers preventing unauthorised update initiation. The UK PSTI Act 2024 requires secure update mechanisms.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Architecture'}, {'question': 'An IoT deployment uses MQTT as its messaging protocol with no authentication configured on the broker. What can an attacker who gains network access do?', 'options': [{'text': 'An attacker can only read MQTT messages but cannot publish commands to IoT devices', 'explanation': 'An unauthenticated MQTT broker allows both subscribing to all topics and publishing to all topics. Attackers can both read all device data and send commands to any device on the broker.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'An attacker can subscribe to all topics reading all device telemetry and publish commands to any device on the broker controlling all connected IoT devices', 'explanation': 'Correct. An unauthenticated MQTT broker gives any network-connected attacker complete visibility of all device data and full command capability over all connected devices. This is a critical vulnerability found routinely on exposed MQTT brokers. Shodan regularly discovers thousands of unauthenticated MQTT brokers accessible from the internet.', 'correct': True}, {'text': 'An unauthenticated MQTT broker is only exploitable if the attacker knows the specific topic names used by the devices', 'explanation': 'MQTT brokers support wildcard subscriptions using # allowing attackers to subscribe to all topics simultaneously without knowing specific topic names. Authentication is not topic-knowledge-dependent.', 'correct': False}, {'text': 'MQTT without authentication is only a risk if the broker is exposed to the internet not on internal networks', 'explanation': 'Unauthenticated MQTT brokers are exploitable from any network including internal networks. Malware with network access, compromised devices on the same network, and insider threats can all exploit unauthenticated brokers.', 'correct': False}], 'overall_explanation': 'MQTT security requirements: enable authentication with unique credentials per device, implement TLS encryption for all broker connections, use access control lists limiting which devices can publish to which topics, deploy broker monitoring for suspicious subscription patterns, and never expose MQTT brokers directly to the internet. MQTT over TLS on port 8883 is the secure configuration.', 'domain': 'IoT Security - Architecture'}]